Formal logic has a precise syntax, just like any programming language. Propositional logic builds statements out of: Letters (or words) for atomic propositions, often called propositional variables or just variables . The logical connectives \(\wedge\) (and), \(\vee\) (or), \(
eg\) (not), \(	o\) (implies / if – then –), \(\leftrightarrow\) (iff / – if and only if –). Parentheses '(' and ')' to avoid ambiguity. The statements in the logic are sometimes called formulas or formulae . These are both acceptable plurals of formula . Sometimes, instead of 'formula', people say well formed formula or wff (which you can pronounce 'woof' as in the sound made by a dog) to emphasise that there are strings of symbols, such as \[p\; \vee\; 	o \;q \;r \;
eg \qquad 	ext{ or } \qquad (\;(\;p\;(\;q\;(\;(\;\wedge\;
eg \] which are (in programming terms) 'syntax errors' and are not 'well formed'. The use of single letters for propositional variables saves a lot of effort, but can lead to less intelligible expressions. In computer science, the importance of meaningful identifiers in programming is well known. So, we may sometimes write logical expressions like this: \[\mathit{theSunIsShiningToday} 	o (
eg \mathit{itIsRaining} \vee \mathit{itIsWarmOutsideToday})\] rather than just \(s 	o (
eg r \vee w)\) . It is important not to be misled by imagining that using meaningful names for propositions makes any difference to the logical content. The meaningful names are very useful for humans, but the two logical expressions above would be treated in the same way when processed by software dealing with logic.

Imagine a room with a light, a light switch and a TV. Consider the following propositions. \[  egin{array}{|l|l|} \mathsf{Proposition~ Symbol} & \mathsf{Meaning}\ \hline \mathit{tvOK} & \mathsf{the~ TV~ is~ working}\ \mathit{power} & \mathsf{there~ has~ not~ been~ a~ power~ cut}\ \mathit{lampLit} & \mathsf{the~ lamp~ is~ lit}\ \mathit{harryAlone} & \mathsf{Harry~ is~ alone~ in~ the~ room}\ \mathit{bulbDead} & \mathsf{the~ light~ bulb~ in~ the~ lamp~ is~ dead}\ \mathit{switchOn} & \mathsf{the~ lamp~ switch~ is~ on}\ \mathit{harryOff} & \mathsf{Harry~ switched~ the~ lamp~ off}\ \hline \end{array} \] We can represent this knowledge about the world in general If Harry is alone and didn't switch the light off, it is still switched on. \( egin{equation} (\mathit{harryAlone} \wedge 
eg \mathit{harryOff}) 	o \mathit{switchOn} \end{equation}\) If the TV is working then there can't be a power cut. \( egin{equation} \mathit{tvOK} 	o \mathit{power} \end{equation}\) If the lamp is not lit and it's switched on and there isn't a power cut then the light bulb is dead. \( egin{equation} (
eg \mathit{lampLit} \wedge \mathit{switchOn} \wedge \mathit{power}) 	o \mathit{bulbDead} \end{equation}\) Suppose we also know these facts about this particular scenario: The TV is working. \( egin{equation}\mathit{tvOK}\end{equation}\) Harry didn't switch the lamp off. \( egin{equation} 
eg \mathit{harryOff} \end{equation}\) Harry is alone in the room. \( egin{equation} \mathit{harryAlone} \end{equation}\) The lamp isn't lit. \( egin{equation} 
eg \mathit{lampLit} \end{equation}\) The question is: Must the bulb be dead? That is, can we be sure the following must be true? \[\mathit{bulbDead}\]

