What properties should we insist connection has if it is to model the way we expect regions of space to behave? The axioms for the RCC can be found in the 1992 paper by Randell, Cui and Cohn, which is available from this page at Leeds . There are different possibilities for how these are presented and here we will use an equivalent formulation from J. G. Stell, Boolean Connection Algebras (2000) . The way the axioms are set out below differs from some of the first order logic we have seen so far. So first let's explain the notation. When there is a unary predicate symbol, \(P\) , in our logic, we have seen we can write \( orall x \; (P(x) 	o \phi)\) where \(\phi\) is a formula involving \(x\) . An alternative is to name all the elements of the domain, \(D\) , that satisfy \(P\) as a set \(A\) where \(A = \{x \in D \mid P(x)\}\) . Then instead of \( orall x \; (P(x) 	o \phi)\) we can write \( orall x \in A\; \phi\) . When several variables are quantified in the same way they can be grouped together. That is instead of \( orall x  orall y  orall z \ldots\) we can just write \( orall x, y, z \ldots\) . Function symbols are used which are to be interpreted by functions that may only be defined on part of the domain and which take values in a specified part of the domain. Suppose we want a model with a function \(f: A 	o B\) where \(A\) and \(B\) are subsets of the domain defined by unary predicates \(a\) and \(b\) . Then using the machinery we have already seen, we can have a predicate \(P\) where \(P(x,y)\) means applying \(f\) to \(x\) gives \(y,\) or \(y = f(x)\) . We would need to state: \[  egin{array}{l}  orall x \in A\; \exists y \in B\; P(x,y),\  orall x \in A\;  orall y, z \in B\; ((P(x,y) \wedge P(x,z)) 	o y = z). \end{array} \] In addition, having the function symbol \(f\) means we can write expressions like: \[  orall x \in A\; \ldots f(x) \ldots \] Instead of having to say: \[  orall x \in A\; \exists y\; P(x,y) 	o \ldots y \ldots \] The idea behind the formal axioms is that a model of the RCC axioms consists of: a set, \(R\) , the elements of which are the regions a special region \(\univ\) for the universe, or the whole space an element, which is not a region, called \(
ull\) for a null element an operation \(\compl\) (complement) which gives for each region (except \(\univ\) ) the outside of the region. an operation, \(\sum\) , giving the union of a pair of regions an operation, \(\prod\) , on regions giving their intersection (when it exists), or giving the null element when the regions do not overlap the binary relation of connection, \(C\) . In more formal language: A model of the region-connection calculus consists of a set \(R\) , an element \(\univ \in R\) , a singleton set \(\{
ull\}\) disjoint from \(R\) , a unary operation \(\compl : R - \{\univ\} ightarrow R - \{\univ\}\) , binary operations \(\sum : R 	imes R ightarrow R\) , and \(\prod : R 	imes R ightarrow R \cup \{
ull\}\) , and a binary relation \(C\) on \(R\) . These data are required to satisfy the following axioms, which make use of the relations derived from \(C\) defined earlier. I have added an informal expression of the idea behind each axiom below it. \[  egin{array}{ll} \mathsf{R1.} & \A x \in R \;\; C (x,x)\ & \mathsf{every~ region~ is~ connected~ to~ itself}\[1ex] \mathsf{R2.} & \A x, y \in R \; (C(x,y) 	o C(y,x))\ & \mathsf{connection~ is~ symmetric}\[1ex] \mathsf{R3.} & \A x \in R \;\; C(x, \univ)\ & \mathsf{all~ regions~ are~ connected~ to~ the~ universal~ region}\[1ex] \mathsf{R4a.} & \A x \in R \; \A y \in R - \{\univ\} \; (C(x, \compl y) \leftrightarrow 
eg NTPP(x, y))\ & \mathsf{being~NTPP~of~} y \mathsf{~means~not~being~connected~to~complement~of~} y\[1ex] \mathsf{R4b.} & \A x \in R \; \A y \in R - \{\univ\} \; (O(x, \compl y) \leftrightarrow 
eg P(x, y))\ & \mathsf{being~part~of~} y \mathsf{~means~not~overlapping~complement~of~} y\[1ex] \mathsf{R5.} & \A x, y, z \in R \; (C(x, \sum (y, z) \leftrightarrow (C(x,y) \vee C(x,z)))\ & \mathsf{connected~to~a~sum~means~connected~to~a~summand } \[1ex] \mathsf{R6.} & \A x, y, z \in R \; (\prod (y,z) \in R 	o\ & \qquad C(x, \prod (y,z)) \leftrightarrow \E w \in R \; (P(w, y) \wedge P(w, z) \wedge C(x, w)))\ & \mathsf{connected~ to~ an~ intersection~ means~ connected~ to~ a~ region}\ & \mathsf{which~ is~ a~ part~ of~ both~ the~ intersecting~ regions}\[1ex] \mathsf{R7.} & \A x, y \in R \; (\prod(x, y) \in R \leftrightarrow O(x, y))\[1ex] \mathsf{R8.} & \A x \in R \; \E y \in R \;\; NTPP(y, x)\ & \mathsf{every~ region~ has~a~ non}	ext{-}\mathsf{tangential~ proper~part~} \end{array} \] Axiom R7 was later found to be redundant. This means it can be proved from the other ones.
